    "pres.h1":"Presentations", "built.h1":"How this site came to be", "built.sub":"A candid note on building this site with AI assistance", "built.intro":"In keeping with a session about using AI responsibly, here is an honest account of how the site itself was made. It was built over about two days of focused work by Miguel Guhlin working with Claude, an AI assistant. A person directed every decision: what to build, which quotes to use, and what is appropriate for a criminal defense audience. The figures below are rough estimates, offered in the same spirit of candor the session asks of any AI-assisted work.", "built.figH":"Three figures", "built.whyH":"Why the human estimate is that large", "built.takeH":"The takeaway", "built.disclaim":"These figures are estimates for illustration. The point is transparency about how AI-assisted work actually comes together, not precision to the hour.", "quotes.h1":"Quotes on AI and the defense", "quotes.sub":"What lawyers and judges are saying about artificial intelligence in legal practice", "quotes.intro":"Every quote used across this site, gathered in one place. Each is verbatim and links to its original source.", "quotes.note":"Quotations appear in their original English. Language switching translates the page around them, not the speakers’ own words.", "about.h":"About this session", "about.p":"This session examines the ethical use of generative AI in criminal defense practice, with a focus on attorney responsibility, accuracy, confidentiality, and professional judgment. You will see where AI tools can assist legal work, where they present ethical risks, and how you remain fully accountable for all AI-assisted output. Through fictional scenarios and hands-on practice, we address common failures such as hallucinated case law and data-privacy concerns, and we build structured prompting and source-grounded habits that reduce risk. No AI subscription is required to attend. A laptop or device with a keyboard is recommended.", "about.objH":"Learning objectives", "about.objLead":"By the end you will be able to:", "about.obj1":"Identify ethical risks tied to AI use in legal practice", "about.obj2":"Explain why you remain responsible for AI-assisted work product", "about.obj3":"Recognize when AI use implicates confidentiality or competence", "about.obj4":"Apply guardrails and verification to reduce AI-related errors", "about.obj5":"Use structured prompting and source-grounded workflows for accuracy", "about.startH":"Start here", "about.startP":"You are on the About page. For the whole session in one place, follow the <a href=\"#walkthrough\">participant walkthrough</a> below from top to bottom: the warm-up assessment, the three segments with their slides and activities, then everything to take home.", "about.wtTag":"Guide", "about.wtCard":"Every deck, activity, and handout in the order we use them, start to finish.", "about.wtH":"Session walkthrough", "about.wtP":"Every piece of the session, in the order we use it. Work top to bottom during the session, or jump back to any piece afterward.", "news.h1":"AI in the Courts", "tut.h1":"Build a LegalAI Project in Claude", "tut.sub":"A step-by-step way to give Claude a persistent, grounded defense workspace", "news.sub":"Real cases, rulings, and coverage on AI in legal practice", "pres.sub":"Four self-contained decks, each with speaker notes.",
